= Los liberados

The president-elect wants a gesture, and the gesture is men.

Vallejo first, then Campa, in the last days of July: eleven years, and the state hands each of them a release paper as if returning an umbrella it had borrowed. There is no apology, because an apology would name the crime, and the crime was theirs by statute: *disolución social*, Article 145, the law that made society a thing two railwaymen could dissolve. The article itself is being repealed — quietly, as part of the new administration's redecorating — which means the men who served eleven years under it were imprisoned, the state now concedes by implication, for grammar.

Campa walks out lighter than his file. Vallejo walks out asking about the pension tables. Neither man blinks at the cameras, having had eleven years to practice not giving the guards a face worth photographing.

The '68 prisoners will follow across the next two years, in twos and threes, many of them put on planes — to Chile, mostly, President Allende's Chile, exile dressed as liberation so that the release papers need never say *innocent*. Every freed man is a gift with a ribbon of implication: *the new sexenio is generous. Note who is generous. Note what gratitude costs, and to whom it is payable.*

- @recibir: Receive them with a public act. Let the city see who is coming home, and who kept the list of names.
- @discreto: Quietly. The DFS photographs every abrazo at that gate, and gratitude is the regime's favorite currency.

