The hall is full an hour early; the aisles fill next; the street outside fills last, and stays. The speeches are short because nothing needs explaining to this audience. Campa says thirteen words about the pension tables of the railway workers — updated, in his head, through eleven years of cell light — and sits down to the longest ovation the Party has heard since the thirties, from railwaymen who were apprentices when he went in and are grandfathers now.

It is a great day, and it is also noted. Somewhere in Bucareli a functionary adds a page to a file and a line to a budget estimate: *these people can be moved by gratitude. Worth testing.* The apertura has your measurements now.

