Two cars, a side street, coffee in a kitchen in Colonia Guerrero with the radio on out of old habit, because a radio complicates the microphones. Campa asks for the membership figures before he asks for the news. Vallejo asks for the railway figures and corrects them from memory. Neither man asks about the men who put them inside — not from serenity, you understand after a while, but from economy: they have eleven years to spend and no intention of spending a peso of it on jailers.

The city does not see them come home. The DFS gets no photograph. And the Party banks, in silence, the only asset the state could not devalue at that gate: two men it failed to break, returned to circulation.
